If you want to update trusted apps keys programatically, currently, you have a very hard time doing.  Naively, you might do this:

{code:java}
Application app = trustedAppsManager.getApplication(name);
app.setPublicKey(newKey);
trustedAppsManager.saveApplication(app);
{code}

This leaves the old keys lying around, which particularly causes an issue if you trust yourself.

KeyStore doesn't offer a method to delete the old keys, the only way, without resorting to using Hibernate directly, is to delete the trusted app and recreate it.  But, if you do that, you'll likely get a unique constraint violation, because the name of the trusted app must be unique, this is enforced by the database, and Hibernate does not necessarily perform actions when it flushes in the order in which you coded them, so there's a good chance that it will insert the new one before deleting the old one.  The work around is to get a hold of the current session, and flush it after deleting the trusted app, which is not pretty at all.

This has caused issues for AppLinks 2.x in Studio, and is likely to cause issues in UAL.

